[2026-04-28--19:53:59]User: What is the highest mountain in the world

[2026-04-28--19:54:04]Agent: Mount Everest is the highest mountain above sea level, at 8,848.86 meters (29,031.7 feet).

If you measure from base to summit (including underwater base), Mauna Kea in Hawaii is taller.
[2026-04-28--19:54:04]User: 
When was it first climbed

[2026-04-28--19:54:13]Agent: Mount Everest was first climbed on May 29, 1953, by Sir Edmund Hillary of New Zealand and Tenzing Norgay, as part of a British expedition led by John Hunt. The summit was reached via the Southeast Ridge route. (There were earlier expeditions and attempts, including the 1924 British expedition with Mallory and Irvine who disappeared.)
[2026-04-28--19:54:13]User: 
Why did they do it

[2026-04-28--19:54:30]Agent: A few key motivations behind the Everest ascent:

- The ultimate mountaineering challenge: Everest was (and is) seen as the world's highest, most difficult peak. Climbers wanted to push human limits and prove what was possible.

- National pride and the “race” to climb it: The 1953 British expedition came after decades of attempts and carried a sense of national prestige and achievement in the postwar era.

- Scientific and exploratory interest: The expedition aimed to test equipment, study high-altitude physiology, and map a reliable route (the Southeast Ridge) for future climbers.

- Personal drive: Hillary and Norgay were motivated by adventure, the opportunity to accomplish a historic feat, and the fulfillment of a long-standing dream for many climbers of that era.

- Aftermath and legacy: Hillary, in particular, used the fame to support the Himalayan Trust, funding schools and clinics in Nepal.

A famous phrase often linked to this spirit is “Because it is there,” attributed to Mallory, capturing the allure of tackling such a peak. Would you like more details on any of these points?
